'''Theatre practitioner''' is a modern term to describe someone who both creates [[theatre|theatrical]] [[performance]]s and who produces a [[theory|theoretical]] [[discourse]] that informs his or her practical work.<ref>Milling and Ley (2001, vi, 173) and Pavis (1998, 280). {{lang-de|Theaterpraktiker}}, {{lang-fr|praticien}}, {{lang-es|teatrista}}.</ref> A theatre practitioner may be a [[Theatre director|director]], a [[dramatist]], an [[actor]], or—characteristically—often a combination of these traditionally-separate roles. "Theatre practice" describes the collective work that various theatre practitioners do.<ref>Pavis (1998, 392).</ref>
The term is not ordinarily applied to theatre-makers prior to the rise of [[modernism]] in the theatre, instead describing theatre [[Praxis (process)|praxis]] from [[Constantin Stanislavski|Stanislavski]]'s development of his '[[Stanislavski's 'system'|system]]', through [[Vsevolod Meyerhold|Meyerhold]]'s [[Biomechanics (Meyerhold)|biomechanics]], [[Antonin Artaud]]'s [[Theatre of cruelty]], [[Bertolt Brecht]]'s [[Epic theatre|epic]] and [[Jerzy Grotowski]]'s [[poor theatre]], down to the present day, with contemporary theatre practitioners including [[Augusto Boal]] with his [[Theatre of the Oppressed]], [[Dario Fo]]'s popular theatre, [[Eugenio Barba]]'s theatre anthropology and [[Anne Bogart]]'s [[viewpoints]].<ref>McCullough (1996, 15-36) and Milling and Ley (2001, vii, 175).</ref>
